{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:57:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:57:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1475"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1475"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.09,0.01,0.34,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102184"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1475"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84648"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"772"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"},{"type":"tags","id":"6584"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35648"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102184"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is retrieved to a major trauma centre after being involved in a motor vehicle crash. The incident occurred approximately three hours prior to his arrival at the Emergency Department. The patient is currently in C-spine precautions with a collar in-situ and is speaking in full sentences. His blood pressure is 115/75 mmHg, pulse 114/min, respiratory rate 24/min and SpO2 97% on room air. On examination, there is an obvious deformity of the left lower limb. The posterior tibial and dorsalis pedis pulses are impalpable and the foot is pale in appearance and feels cold. An X-ray of the affected limb is taken and shown below (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Following analgesia, which one of the following is the next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent angiogram","Urgent CT angiogram","Urgent MR angiogram","Reduce in theatre on the emergency list","Reduce in the emergency department"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has suffered a posterior knee dislocation and patella fracture with compression of the popliteal artery. As such, circulation is compromised and the viability of the foot is very much at risk. Therefore, the knee needs to be \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced\u003C/strong\u003E as soon as possible to re-establish circulation to the periphery. Following reduction, a neurovascular assessment must be performed. If closed reduction is not possible then the patient must be taken to theatre for an open approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKnee dislocations are rare, but a significant number have serious neurovascular complications. Posterior dislocations are due to axial load to the flexed knee (seen in car accidents with \u0027dashboard injury\u0027) and have the the highest rate of vascular injury (25%) for all knee dislocation injuries. Knee dislocations are invariably associated with ligament injuries, the most common pattern being bi-cruciate ligament tears with either MCL or posterolateral corner involvement. Fractures of the distal femur or proximal tibia are also common (~15%).\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Joint dislocations with circulatory compromise require prompt reduction to re-establish circulation","Posterior knee dislocations have a high rate of popliteal artery injury"],"references":["Robertson A, Nutton R, Keating J. Dislocation of the Knee. J Bone Joint Surg Br. 2006;88(6):706-11. doi:10.1302/0301-620X.88B6.17448"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84648"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1475"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16360"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16360"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/556b2a7f-a704-4186-88e9-7b0a372b4a93.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/556b2a7f-a704-4186-88e9-7b0a372b4a93.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":718,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84648"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T09:16:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T09:16:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1475"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102184"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"}